WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:01.834
therefore this derivation wouldn't work.

00:03.256 --> 00:05.039
Now why is this important?

00:05.099 --> 00:19.241
Because if you look back into your drawing, what you're basically doing is you are imposing a quadratic regularizer around this initial point right here.

00:20.263 --> 00:27.895
And that creates this very strong connection between the end gradient and the initial gradient.

00:27.875 --> 00:40.266
So now when you're optimizing, when you have a training loss of the inner task, and maybe the training loss looks something like, it looks something like, like this right here.

00:41.968 --> 00:48.814
So SGD will, it would go right to the very inner point right here.

00:49.094 --> 00:51.656
If you're just let SGD run, it would go there.

00:52.117 --> 00:57.882
But now since you have this regularizer, SGD needs to find a trade off point between the two.

00:57.862 --> 01:02.131
So what it will do is it will probably go somewhere and stop somewhere here.

01:02.693 --> 01:04.897
So it will now have two forces pulling on it.

01:05.058 --> 01:16.242
The first force will be this quantity right here and the second force will be pulling it back towards this.

01:16.222 --> 01:23.480
You can pretty much count, so now SGD cannot just go to any point right here.

01:23.520 --> 01:25.465
It cannot go to any isoline.

01:25.485 --> 01:26.769
These are not equal anymore.

01:27.731 --> 01:33.285
Mainly it will go to the one point that points into the direction of this quadratic right here.

01:33.265 --> 01:44.476
So since it's a quadratic, we have closed form formulas for relating one gradient on the quadratic, namely the one out here, with the gradient back here.

01:44.516 --> 02:02.715
So we can express this Jacobian in closed form because this is a quadratic, because we have this regularizer, because you have these basically two forces pulling on this point in opposite direction, one pointing towards the training loss and one pointing towards the inside of the quadratic.

02:02.695 --> 02:06.202
So that's why this method works.

02:07.084 --> 02:08.387
Okay.

02:09.709 --> 02:13.317
I can recommend Farin Hussar's blog post.

02:13.417 --> 02:19.991
He has some very nice animations of why this basically restricts where gradient descent can go.

02:21.554 --> 02:23.638
I can link to it in the description.

02:24.300 --> 02:25.041
